case_name: Prabhu v. Ramdey, Yadram and Nathu

facts.text: Appellant Prabhu is the owner of agricultural land bearing Khasra Nos. 224, 215, 244, 299, 320, 506, 617 and 687 situated in village Nilakpur, Tehsil Behror, District Alwar, Rajasthan.

anchor.surface_text: The appellant Prabhu is the owner of agricultural land bearing Khasra Nos. 224, 215, 244, 299, 320, 506, 617 and 687 situated in village Nilakpur, Tehsil Behror, District Alwar, in the State of Rajasthan.

facts.text: Appellant's father Jora executed a usufructuary mortgage of the said land in about 1936 for a period of twenty years in favour of one Ganga Din.

anchor.surface_text: The appellants father Jora had executed a usufructuary mortgage of the said land in about 1936 for a period of twenty years in favour of one Ganga Din.

facts.text: Appellant obtained a decree for redemption on July 16, 1956 declaring mortgage and encumbrances extinguished and directing mortgagee to deliver possession.

anchor.surface_text: After the expiry of the period prescribed by the said mortgage, the appellant obtained a decree for redemption on July 16, 1956. This decree declared that the mortgage and all encumbrances created by the mortgagee or any person claiming under him were extinguished and directed the mortgagee to deliver possession of the mortgaged property to the appellant.

facts.text: During continuance of mortgage, mortgagee Ganga Din let out the land to respondents 1 to 3: Ramdey, Yadram and Nathu.

anchor.surface_text: It appears that during the continuance of the mortgage, the mortgagee Ganga Din had let out the aforesaid land to respondents I to 3 Ramdey, Yadram and Nathu respectively.

facts.text: Rajasthan Tenancy Act, 1955 came into force on October 15, 1955.

anchor.surface_text: Meanwhile, on October 15,1955 the Rajasthan Tenancy Act, 1955  No. 3 of 1955   hereinafter called the Act  had come into force.

facts.text: Appellant instituted suit for possession against three respondents on July 28, 1956.

anchor.surface_text: On July 28, 1956, the appellant instituted the present suit for possession of the land in question against the three respondents.

facts.text: Suit tried by Sub-Divisional Officer, Behror, who dismissed it finding respondents not trespassers.

anchor.surface_text: This suit was tried by the Sub- Divisional Officer, Behror. ... He found that the ,respondents were not trespassers as alleged by the appellant and as such the appellant was not entitled to any relief. In the result, the appellants suit was dismissed.

facts.text: Appellant alleged that after redemption decree, respondents delivered possession but trespassed back a few days later.

anchor.surface_text: In this suit the appellant had alleged that after the redemption decree had been passed in favour of the appellant, the respondents had in fact delivered possession of the property to the appellant, but a few days thereafter they had trespassed into the property and obtained its possession wrongfully.

facts.text: Respondents resisted plea denying surrender of possession and claimed rights under the Act.

anchor.surface_text: This plea was resisted by the respondents on the ground that they had not surrendered possession of the property to the appellant as alleged by him and that under the relevant provisions of the Act they were entitled to remain in possession of this property.

facts.text: Appeal by appellant to Additional Commissioner, Ajmer, who reversed trial court and held appellant entitled to eject respondents.

anchor.surface_text: Against this decision the appellant preferred an appeal before the Additional Commissioner, Ajmer. The appellate authority reversed the finding of the trial court and held that the appellant was entitled to eject the respondents.

facts.text: Respondents' second appeal to Board of Revenue, Rajasthan, Ajmer succeeded, restoring trial court order.

anchor.surface_text: The respondents challenged the correctness of this order by preferring a second appeal before the Board of Revenue for Rajasthan, Ajmer. Their appeal succeeded and consequently, the order passed by the appellate authority was set aside and that passed by the trial judge was restored.

facts.text: Board held respondents' possession protected by s.15 of Act, ejectment only per Act, none proved.

anchor.surface_text: The Board has held that by virtue of the provisions of s. 15 of the Act, the possession of the respondents was unassailable and they could be ejected only in accordance with the relevant section of the said Act. Since none of the grounds available to the appellant under the Act had been proved, he was not entitled to a claim for ejectment.

facts.text: Appellant filed writ petition in Rajasthan High Court under Art. 226 challenging Board's order, dismissed on October 20, 1961.

anchor.surface_text: The validity of the Boards decision was challenged by the appellant by moving the Rajasthan High Court in its writ jurisdiction under Art. 226 of the Constitution. ... This petition, however, failed and was dismissed by the High Court.

facts.text: Appeal to Supreme Court by special leave: Civil Appeal No. 323 of 1963.

anchor.surface_text: CIVIL APPELLATE JURISDICTION Civil Appeal No. 323 of 1963. Appeal by special leave from the judgment and order dated October 20, 1961 of the Rajasthan High Court in D. B. Civil Writ No. 41 of 1959.

facts.text: Relevant facts no longer in dispute: father created usufructuary mortgage, respondents admitted as tenants during mortgage, mortgage redeemed, respondents continued in possession.

anchor.surface_text: The relevant facts, in the light of which the question of law raised before us by Mr. Misra on behalf of the appellant has to be considered, are no longer in dispute. The appellants father created a usufructuary mortgage of the land and during the continuance of the said mortgage the respondents were admitted as tenants.

facts.text: Appellant's plea that respondents were trespassers after surrendering post-decree not proved.

anchor.surface_text: That plea has not been proved and the matter falls to be considered squarely within, the provisions of ss.15 and 161 of the Act.

facts.text: Respondents satisfy definition of tenant under s.5(43) of Act as rent payable.

anchor.surface_text: Tenant has been defined by s. 5(43) of the Act as meaning a person by whom rent is or but for a contract, express or implied, would be payable ... The test prescribed by this definition is that the person can claim to be a tenant if it is shown that rent is payable by him in respect of the land. That test is clearly satisfied by the three respondents in the present case.

facts.text: Respondents do not fall within definition of trespasser under s.5(44) of Act.

anchor.surface_text: A trespasser has been defined by S. 5(44) of the Act as meaning a person who takes or retains possession of unoccupied land without authority or who prevents another person from occupying land duly let out to him. ... It is plain that the respondents do not fall within the definition of trespasser as prescribed by this clause.

facts.text: On Oct 15, 1955 commencement, respondents became Khatedar tenants under s.15 of Act.

anchor.surface_text: Section 15 provides, inter alia, that subject to the provisions of s.16 every person who, at the commencement of this Act, is a tenant of land, shall ... become Khatedars by virtue of the statutory provisions prescribed by s. 15.

facts.text: No tenant ejectable except under Act per s.161.

anchor.surface_text: Section 161 of the Act provides that no tenant shall be ejected from his holding otherwise than in accordance with the provisions of this Act.

facts.text: S.183 for ejectment of trespassers has no application as respondents not trespassers.

anchor.surface_text: It is true that s. 183. of the Act provides for the ejectment of a trespasser but that section has no application to this case inasmuch as the respondents cannot be held to be trespassers at all.

facts.text: Supreme Court dismissed appeal with costs to respondent No.1.

anchor.surface_text: In the result, the view taken by the Board about the status of the respondents is right and the High Court was, therefore, justified in dismissing the appellants writ petition filed before it. The appeal therefore fails and is dismissed with costs. Costs in favour of respondent No.

holdings.text: The three respondents satisfy the test prescribed by the definition of tenant under s. 5(43) of the Act and are tenants since rent is payable by them in respect of the land.

anchor.surface_text: Tenant has been defined by s. 5(43) of the Act as meaning a person by whom rent is or but for a contract, express or implied, would be payable ... The test prescribed by this definition is that the person can claim to be a tenant if it is shown that rent is payable by him in respect of the land.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Direct application of statutory definition of tenant to facts of respondents paying rent.

holdings.text: The respondents do not fall within the definition of trespasser under s. 5(44) of the Act.

anchor.surface_text: A trespasser has been defined by S. 5(44) of the Act as meaning a person who takes or retains possession of unoccupied land without authority or who prevents another person from occupying land duly let out to him. ... It is plain that the respondents do not fall within the definition of trespasser as prescribed by this clause.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Statutory definition does not match respondents' possession authorized by mortgagee.

holdings.text: As soon as s. 15 came into operation on October 15, 1955, the respondents who were tenants inducted by the mortgagee became Khatedar tenants entitled to rights and subject to liabilities under the Act.

anchor.surface_text: Let us now refer to s. 15 as it stood at the relevant time. Section 15 provides, inter alia, that subject to the provisions of s.16 every person who, at the commencement of this Act, is a tenant of land, shall ... In other words, as soon as s. 1.5 came into operation on October 15, 1955, the possession of the respondents, who had been inducted into the land by the mortgagee was substantially altered and they became Khatedars by virtue of the statutory provisions prescribed by s. 1 5.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Statutory operation of s.15 on existing tenants at commencement regardless of how inducted.

holdings.text: No tenant including the respondents who became Khatedars under s.15 shall be ejected from his holding otherwise than in accordance with the provisions of the Act per s.161.

anchor.surface_text: Section 161 of the Act provides that no tenant shall be ejected from his holding otherwise than in accordance with the provisions of this Act. The position thus is clear that as soon as the Act came into force the respondents were entitled to the benefits of s. 15 and cannot be ejected except under the provisions of the Act in view of s. 161.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Combined application of ss.15 and 161 to protect Khatedar tenants from ejectment outside Act.

holdings.text: Section 183 providing for ejectment of trespassers has no application because the respondents are not trespassers.

anchor.surface_text: It is true that s. 183. of the Act provides for the ejectment of a trespasser but that section has no application to this case inasmuch as the respondents cannot be held to be trespassers at all.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Prerequisite of trespasser status not met per s.5(44).

holdings.text: The appellant's plea that respondents surrendered possession after redemption decree and then trespassed back has not been proved.

anchor.surface_text: That plea has not been proved and the matter falls to be considered squarely within, the provisions of ss.15 and 161 of the Act.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Lack of proof leads to application of ss.15/161 assuming continued tenant status.

holdings.text: The general rule from Mahabir Gope that leases by mortgagee terminate on redemption is subject to exception where statute confers rights on such tenants, as here under s.15.

anchor.surface_text: Mr. Misra, however, contends that there are two decisions of this Court which support his case... In Mahabir Gope... this Court has held that as a general rule... but this Court has taken the precaution to point out that even in regard to tenants inducted into the land by a mortgagee cases may arise where the said tenants may acquire rights of special character by virtue of statutory provisions... That is precisely what has happened in the present case.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Precedent itself recognizes statutory exceptions; s.15 provides such rights here.

holdings.text: Harihar Prasad decision does not lay down any general proposition applicable here as it turns on specific provisions of Bihar Tenancy Act which conferred no statutory benefit on mortgagee tenants unlike Rajasthan Act s.15.

anchor.surface_text: The other decision on which Mr. Misra relies is Harihar Prasad Singh... In that case it was held that the persons inducted by mortgagees could not be raiyats... This conclusion, however, flows from the basic fact that the mortgagees... were neither proprietors nor tenure holders... This decision therefore does not lay down any general proposition on which Mr. Misra can possibly rely.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Precedent distinguished on basis of differing statutory scheme in Bihar Act.

holdings.text: The view taken by the Board of Revenue about the status of the respondents as protected Khatedar tenants is correct; appellant not entitled to ejectment; appeal dismissed.

anchor.surface_text: In the result, the view taken by the Board about the status of the respondents is right and the High Court was, therefore, justified in dismissing the appellants writ petition filed before it. The appeal therefore fails and is dismissed with costs.

holdings.reasoning_summary: Synthesis of statutory applications and precedent distinctions affirms lower tribunal's legal conclusion.

anchor.surface_text: In Mahabir Gope and Others v. Harbans Narain Singh and Others 1 , this Court has held that as a general rule a person cannot, by transfer or otherwise, confer a better title on another than he himself had. A mortgagee cannot, therefore, create an interest in the mortgaged property which will enure beyond the termination of his interest as mortgagee. In consequence any lease granted by a morgagee in possession must come to an end at redemption.
